title: Girls basketball roundup: Willmar can't close against mighty Alexandria
text:
Girls basketball roundup: Willmar can’t close against mighty Alexandria
State-ranked Alex rallies from a slow start to blast Willmar 76-45. Other winners Thursday include: ACGC, BBE, Paynesville, BOLD and Lakeview.
ALEXANDRIA — The Willmar girls basketball team couldn’t turn a great start and a decent first half into a good second half Thursday night.
It added up to a 76-45 Central Lakes Conference for Alexandria.
ADVERTISEMENT
Alex is now 12-0 in the Central Lakes and 16-3 overall record. Willmar is 5-6 and 10-11. Alex is ranked fourth in the state in Class AAA.
Alex won the first meeting between the teams, 77-59 on Dec. 6 at Willmar.
Willmar started the game with a 7-0 lead. Alex then scored 11 straight to go up 11-7. Alex led 29-21 at halftime, then went on a 14-1 run to start the second half and led 49-26 midway through the final 18 minutes.
Allie Haabala, a 5-foot-7 senior, led Alex with 16 points. Hadley Thul, a 6-2 senior, had 15 and Chloe Scholl, a 5-9 senior, added 14. MaCee Linow, a 5-6 senior, added 11 for Alex.
Willmar junior guard Telilie Lange had 22 points, including 12 in the first half.
Willmar is host to Detroit Lakes at 7:15 p.m. Tuesday in another CLC game at the Big Red Gym.

Central Minnesota
ACGC 54, EVW 37
Atwater-Cosmos-Grove City overcame a 25-22 halftime deficit for the victory over Eden Valley-Watkins at Eden Valley.
“When you trust the process and you stick to your game plan, good things happen,” ACGC head coach Jacklyn Frericks said. “We were down by three at halftime, but we kept doing what we hoped to do.
“We shot really well from the paint. The posts really did the job tonight and the guards did a good job getting them the ball.”
Ruby Klinger had 21 points and eight rebounds for the Falcons. Quinn Eisenbacher added 12 points, eight rebounds and three assists and Brooke Schultz added 11 points and three assists for ACGC.
Addy Stommes, a 5-foot-5 junior, had 13 points to lead the Eagles.
ACGC is host to Upsala at 7:15 p.m. Friday. It’s Parents’ Night in Grove City.

BBE 59, Holdingford 52
Kacey Fischer had 14 points and 10 rebounds and Bree Theischafer added 13 points, three assists and six steals in Belgrade-Brooten-Elrosa’s victory at Holdingford.
Adley Hagen added 10 points and six steals for the Jaguars, who got nine points apiece from Teagan Dingmann and Macey Roering.
BBE plays Browerville/Eagle Valley at 3:30 p.m. Saturday in Belgrade.

The Paynesville Bulldogs routed the Maple Lake Irish at Maple Lake.
Paynesville next plays host to Redwood Valley at 7 p.m. Monday.
Non-conference
BOLD 68, Cedar Mountain 56
Lainey Braulick, a Miss Minnesota Basketball finalist, scored 25 points to lead BOLD past Cedar Mountain at Morgan.
ADVERTISEMENT
Braulick, a 5-foot-8 senior guard, also had four assists and four steals. Ema Flann, a 5-5 eighth-grader, added 18 points, 11 rebounds, four assists and six steals for the Warriors.
Peyton Sander, a 6-0 senior, had 10 points.
The Cougars were led by Aubrey Steffl. The 5-5 sophomore had 14 points. Brooklyn Diehn, a 5-2 senior, Kendra Erickson, a 5-8 sophomore, and Marlie Wildt, a 5-9 sophomore, all had 12 points for Cedar Mountain.
BOLD plays Montevideo in a West Central Conference game at 7 p.m. Friday at Olivia.
